results.notes:
This is the one that got me into mushroom hunting.

We found it (and several others over the course of two days) on the edges of bamboo forests throughout Shikanoshima Island in Fukuoka.

Oddly, these did not have the bad smell that lots of webpages suggested it should have. The slimy dark part had no obvious smell, though it was attracting bugs just fine – maybe my nose is bad. The body and veil, however, smelled like something between earth, apples, and old apples. Full disclosure, I ate a bit bc it smelled so good.

So, i am calling this one Phallus indusiatus, but a Japanese field guide book distinguishes between two types, both of which seem to be considered the same when i search in english. One is called kinugasatake (キヌガサタケ) and the other is makukinugasatake (マクキヌガサタケ .

*I am putting pictures of two specimens – they may be the same, different examples of the two types above, or something completely different. I am a novice so my identifications should not be trusted.

results.notes:
Growing in hardwood forest of birch, beech, oak.
Stipe was buried; the ground and the mushroom were fairly moist. I failed to dig up the entire stipe; looks like there’s at least a small piece of the base missing. But, I don’t see any evidence of a basal bulb. And. the fact that the stipe was well buried suggests section Vaginatae series Penetratrices, which is where stirps Strobilaceovolvata is housed. I believe this classification includes the “ringed ringless Amanita species.”
Spores scoped and a few measurements provided: 11×6; 11×7. 12×9; 12×7. So it looks like we have ellipsoid to almost elongate spores here. Caeareae? At first I thought “maybe.” But, the crusty darkening UV remains on the cap surface point away from section Caesareae. There appears to be some basal volval remains adhered to the part of the stipe base that may be seen.
Material dried and in good condition.

results.notes:
Distinguishing features:

Macroscopic: Growing from wood. The cap was buttery smooth. Cap and gills were tan. Stipe was lighter colored. Upon drying more it became clear that the cap was hygrophanous. The stipe was flatted near the attachment to the cap. The gills were attached (somewhat notched). The spore print was brown, but not sufficient for us to characterize it further (see photo). Taste and smell were farinaceous.

Microscopically: The spores appear to be amygdaliform (see photo), 7.7×4.8 microns (s.d. was 0.5×0.3 microns). Resolution was not good enough to detect other spore characters. Inflated fusiform cystidia were abundant. Their apices seemed to be acuminate to broadly mucronate (again, see photos). Pilial hyphae are inflated.
